title: Reintroduce experimental api changes and fix remote build break
body:
**Description**: This commit reintroduces the payload from this PR: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5805
It also fixes a remote ADO pipeline build break that resulted in the change being reverted

**Motivation and Context**
In this original payload, the reference path for cppwinrt.exe is modified to include the current binary directory so that types in winml_api can be referenced in winml_api_experimental. For some reason this causes a non-descriptive build break on the ADO pipeline, but works fine locally. I discovered that if I explicitly reference the exact file path necessary for winml_api_experimental to reference winml_api, rather than specifying the entire binary directory for every cppwinrt project, the build break resolves.

This may be some esoteric issue hit on the build server where there are cached winmds that cause a circular reference. Not entirely sure.

title: OrtModule v0.21
body:
OrtModule v0.2.

1.	Introduced the YieldOp 
Todos: Need a proper frontend/backend co-design and co-implementation to handle the following common cases (5 dev-days)
-	Case 1: forward_outputs are prediction and loss, but backward_inputs is loss_grad, since prediction_loss is the upstream gradient of loss_grad. 
-	Case 2: forward outputs are loss1 and loss2, backward_inputs are loss1_grad and loss2_grad. 

2.	Implemented ModuleGradientGraphBuilder for building training graph and adding YieldOp
Notes: This is a relative mature components, but it can need more work for supporting the Multi-Yield feature. 

3.	Implemented OrtMessageQueue for passing tensors between Pytorch and ORT
Shortcut: Because OpKernel doesnt have a direct access to the data passed in from InferenceSession API, we introduced a global singleton instance of OrtMessageQueue to facilitate the data exchange between ORT and Pytorch. The singleton approach is a quick-and-dirty PoC to get the data passing working. Due to its singleton nature, we currently doesnt support multi-ORTModule concurrent calls. 
Todos: Redesign, implement and test the data passing mechanism (5 dev-days) 
-	Option 1: Open up a path to pass data from InferenceSession API into ExecutionFrame, so that the OpKernel can access Pytorch tensor. (we also need a similar path to pass ORT tensor to Pytorch) 
-	Option 2. Enrich OrtMessageQueue singleton class so that it can support multi-concurrent runs. 

4.	Introduced a SetOutputMLValue() function for injecting external OrtValue during graph execution
Shortcut: For injecting a torch tensor as YieldOps output, we have replaced its pre-allocated OrtValue pointer with a passed-in ORValue pointer. However, the pre-allocated ORTValue should not be taken into memory plan at the first place. Currently, we are using .Alias() kernel decorator to avoid allocating buffer for Yield Output. 
 Todos: (3 dev-days)
-	Re-exam and explore other designs for injecting external tensor into ORT during the execution of the graph. 
-	If we commit to the current design, we need to introduce a new kernel decorator to exclude the YieldOps output from the memory planning. 

5.	Introduced two InferenceSession APIs and exposed them in ORTModuel forward()/backward() calls
Todos: Discuss with inference team to see if this is good API to add in InferenceSession. Consider the TrainingSession API. (unknown dev-days depending on the future decision) 

6.	Implemented threading patterns for foreground-background thread coordination
Shortcut: currently we are using a single std::thread to invoke the Run() call in the background. This doesnt support multiple concurrent background Run() calls. 
Todos:  (10 dev-days)
a.	Design for the background task data structure for supporting multiple concurrent tasks
b.	Design for a more principled way for foreground-background coordination
c.	Support graceful shutdown, and corner/exception cases
o	Case 1: calling forward() multiple times without calling a backward()
o	Case 2: Stop ORTModule without completing a matching backward() call 
o	Case 3.Handel exception thrown in the forward() call
d.	Unit tests for the implementations

7.	Graph Transformer Fix to enable two op fusions
Todos: MatmulTransposeFusion is a duplication MatMulScaleFusion: need to investigate the limitation of MatMulScaleFusion and deduplicated.  (2 dev-days)

title: Continue memory planning when unknown shape tensor is encountered.
body: Currently we disallow any memory planning to happen when a tensor whose shape cannot be resolved ahead of graph execution for example in graphs that have NonZero op. This results in no memory planning taking places which can affect the total memory footprint at training and/or throughput. It also disables features like contiguous memory allocation that need memory planning. Instead of disabling memory planning altogether we can take a hybrid approach to memory plan as much as possible and dynamically allocate the rest.

title: Add robust dependency check for Python package
body:
**Description**:
- Use the correct version of CUDA when multiple versions are installed on the machine.
  - A .py file is generated during CMake build and then used at runtime to check for the appropriate version of dependencies.
  - cuDNN is expected to be installed at same location as CUDA Toolkit, as described in the official installation instructions from NVIDIA.
  - Python 3.6 and 3.7 rely on PATH environment variable for locating CUDA/cuDNN DLLs, while in Python 3.8 and 3.9 a new API (`os.add_dll_directory`) is used to specify DLL search location.
  - The new method of locating CUDA is also more robust: previously it could happen that everything works just fine if `import torch` is placed before `import onnxruntime`, but an error occurs if the order of these imports is switched (onnxruntime could end up using CUDA DLLs distributed with PyTorch).
- Provide an informative error message to the user in case one of dependencies is missing.
  - **onnxruntime-gpu** package depends on CUDA, cuDNN and C++ Runtime (if built with VS 2019).
  - The missing dependency and the required version are printed as part of the error message.
  - The check for VS 2019 C++ Runtime is now more robust.
- Build **onnxruntime-gpu** Python package for Python 3.8/3.9 in CI.

**Motivation and Context**:
- Having more than one version of CUDA installed on the machine is a quite common scenario. **onnxruntime-gpu** package should work out-of-the-box on such a machine, without the need for manual configuration.
- The users are often confused when `import onnxruntime` complains about not being able to find a DLL - it's not obvious which dependency is missing.
- Python 3.8 edition of **onnxruntime-gpu** package is still missing on PyPI. This change should help producing robust packages for all supported versions of Python.

**Affected components**:
- **onnxruntime** and **onnxruntime-gpu** Python packages for Windows for all versions of Python.

fixes #5697
fixes #5963
fixes #6433
fixes #6435

title: Improve work distribution for Expand operator, and sharded LoopCounter configuration
body:
**Description**: This PR makes two changes identified while looking at a PGAN model.  

First, it uses ThreadPool::TryParallelFor for the main parallel loops in the Expand operator.  This lets the thread pool decide on the granularity at which to distribute work (unlike TrySimpleParallelFor).  Profiling showed high costs when running "simple" loops with 4M iterations each of which copied only 4 bytes.

Second, it updates the sharded loop counter in the thread pool so that the number of shards is capped by the number of threads.  This helps make the performance of any other high-contention "simple" loops more robust at low thread counts by letting each thread work on its own "home" shard for longer.

**Motivation and Context**

Profiling showed a PGAN model taking 2x+ longer with the non-OpenMP build.  The root cause was that the OpenMP build uses simple static scheduling of loop iterations, while the non-OpenMP build uses dynamic scheduling.  The combination of large numbers of tiny iterations is less significant with static scheduling --- although still desirable to avoid, given that each iteration incurs a std::function invocation.

title: Bug 31463811: Servicing: Redist (Nuget) conflicts with Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning starting 21H1+
body:
Bug 31463811: Servicing: Redist (Nuget) conflicts with Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning starting 21H1+

WinML uses LoadLibrary to load onnxruntime.dll and directml.dll.

However, the loading of the library should be sensitive to where the calling library is located.
Currently:
  LoadLibraryExA("onnxruntime.dll", nullptr, LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_SYSTEM32);

However, on Desktop this call will correctly load from System32 but will suffer from ordering issues if the redist is loaded first. If the redist is loaded first, the LoadLibraryExA call will resolve onnxruntime.dll to the one loaded in memory from outside of system32, and ignore the flags LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_SYSTEM32.

In Store Apps this call will completely ignore the LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_SYSTEM32 flag, and only load from the app package (if the redist binary - any binary with the same name - is present there). This causes the binary to be incorrectly loaded from System32 and load onnxruntime from the app package.

title: Add equalization algorithm and example usage
body:
**Description**
This pull request implements part of the paper on [Data-Free Quantization Through Weight Equalization and Bias Correction](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1906.04721.pdf) by Nagel et al. 2019, specifically the equalization algorithm.

**Motivation and Context**
Equalization shows improved performance in data-free quantization in models that see performance loss in depth-wise convolutions. The reference example is MobileNetV2, which observes an accuracy drop when converting from float32 to int8 using quantization. In the reference model, equalization improves IntegerOps accuracy by roughly 10% and improves QLinearOps accuracy by roughly 20%. Both the algorithm and this example result are included.

I presented this work to Microsoft as an intern with Intel Corporation at the Microsoft Technology Center in Folsom, CA. Thank you @yufenglee for considering this request.

title: MLAS: improve quantized depthwise convolution
body:
**Description**: Improve the performance of QLinearConv for depthwise convolutions.

**Motivation and Context**
1) Added support for an im2col variant that returns an array of buffer pointers instead of memcpy'ing the original data (see https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.02129.pdf). This saves memcpy time and reduces the size of the intermediate buffer needed to hold the im2col transform. This im2col will also be used to support quantized pooling ops.
2) Added an AVX2 depthwise convolution kernel.

On an older Broadwell test system, the mobilenetv2-7.quant.onnx from the E2E example drops from 4.6ms to 3.6ms per inference. The original FP32 model runs in 3.2ms on the same system.

title: Support disabling a typed kernel registration that uses the output type
body:
**Description**: 
Update infrastructure to support disabling a typed kernel registration that uses output 0 for the type (vs. the normal use case of input 0).

**Motivation and Context**
Allow type reduction script to disable operators where the output type is used in the typed kernel registration.

body:
